## Key finding (drives the TL;DR)

**No ŌĆö `vehicle_attitude_setpoint` and `vehicle_torque_setpoint` do NOT inject at the same
stage.** They are two stages apart in the cascade, separated by `mc_rate_control`:

```
trajectory_setpoint
  Ōåō  mc_pos_control               (PositionControl::update ŌåÆ ControlMath::thrustToAttitude)
vehicle_attitude_setpoint          ŌåÉ injection point #1 ŌĆö consumed by mc_att_control
  Ōåō  mc_att_control               (AttitudeControl::update ŌĆö quaternion error ŌåÆ desired rates)
vehicle_rates_setpoint
  Ōåō  mc_rate_control              (RateControl::update ŌĆö PID + FF on rate error ŌåÆ torque)
vehicle_torque_setpoint            ŌåÉ injection point #2 ŌĆö consumed by control_allocator
vehicle_thrust_setpoint
  Ōåō  control_allocator            (mixer-matrix solve: u = BŌĆĀ ┬Ę w)
actuator_motors  /  actuator_servos
```

Verified citations:
- `vehicle_attitude_setpoint` is consumed at `mc_att_control_main.cpp:227-237`.
- `vehicle_torque_setpoint`  is consumed at `ControlAllocator.cpp:371-388`.
- Between them runs `mc_rate_control` (subscribed to `vehicle_angular_velocity` callback,
  publishes torque at `MulticopterRateControl.cpp:289`).

Each setpoint enters the cascade at the input of a **different module**. The cascade is
intentionally split this way so that an external source (offboard, MAVLink ATTITUDE_TARGET,
manual mode) can inject at the *attitude* level while normal flight still uses the rate loop
underneath, or so that a manual / acro mode can drive torque directly without an attitude
loop at all.

